AGI - Poland is ready to host nuclear weapons if NATO> decides to deploy them in response to the strengthening of Russian weapons in Belarus and Kaliningrad: President Andrzej Duda said in an interview, provoking a harsh Kremlin warning. Poland, a member of NATO and a convinced supporter of Ukraine, borders the Russian exclave of Kaliningrad and Belarus, ally of Moscow. "If our allies decide to deploy nuclear weapons on our territory as part of nuclear sharing, to strengthen NATO's eastern flank, we are ready to do so," said Duda in an interview published by the daily Fakt.
&nbsp;
The United States' nuclear sharing agreements provide for the deployment and storage of a nuclear arsenal in Europe, allowing non-nuclear weapons to place such weapons on their territory and participate in exercises. In June 2023, Russian President Vladimir Putin confirmed that Moscow sent tactical nuclear weapons to Belarus, which borders Ukraine and Poland. The closeness of Russian nuclear weapons > has long made Poland the pursuit of a more active role in the NATO nuclear sharing mechanism: in 2014, the then Deputy Minister of Defense, Tomasz Szatkowski, declared for the first time the desire of Poland to become a host nation following the annexation of Crimea by Russia precisely that year.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Duda spoke to the Polish media after his visit to New York, where he held meetings at the United Nations and discussed the war in Ukraine with former US President Donald Trump. In March, he had visited Washington for an interview with US President Joe Biden. Discussions on nuclear cooperation between Poland and the United States have been going on for a long time, said the Polish President. "I have to admit that, in response to this, I have declared our readiness," Duda reported about the content of his talks in the United States.
&nbsp;
"The army will obviously analyze the situation and in any case it will take all the necessary response measures > to ensure our safety," said the spokesman of the Kremlin Dmitri Peskov.> For his part, Russian Foreign Minister Serghei Lavrov said that "Western people are dangerously on the brink of a direct military confrontation between nuclear powers." The words of Duda - the close ally of the former party to power in the country, the nationalist Law and Justice - rekindled the spotlight on the open fracture between the Polish presidency and government, after the last October elections, won by the pro-European coalition of Donald Tusk. "I very much care that Poland lives safely, that it is armed as much as possible, but I would also like every possible initiative to be, first of all, well prepared by the responsible," said Prime Minister Tusk.
&nbsp;
According to the Polish Constitution, the President of the Republic is formally the supreme leader of the armed forces and exercises his functions "through" the Minister of Defense. In the field of foreign policy it is required to "cooperate with the competent Prime Minister and Ministers". "I look forward to meeting President Duda," Tusk said. At the Vilnius Summit in 2023, the Allies reaffirmed that NATO will "do everything that is necessary to ensure the credibility, effectiveness and security of its nuclear deterrence mission, including continuing to modernize its nuclear capabilities and updating its planning process." &nbsp;

